As the author points out, he's concerned about the future about dynamic languages on the .net platform in general. IronPython and IronRuby are just two implementations of it.<p>The reason you should care (assuming you're a .net developer) is that the DLR lets you do all sorts of cool things such as the following c# snippet calling python code:<p><pre><code>    ScriptRuntime py = Python.CreateRuntime();
    dynamic random = py.UseFile("random.py");

    //Make an array of numbers
    var items = Enumerable.Range(1, 7).ToArray();
    random.shuffle(items);
</code></pre>
(source: <a href="http://www.hanselman.com/blog/C4AndTheDynamicKeywordWhirlwindTourAroundNET4AndVisualStudio2010Beta1.aspx" rel="nofollow">http://www.hanselman.com/blog/C4AndTheDynamicKeywordWhirlwin...</a>)<p>Being able to have ruby, c#, python, et al all running in the same runtime with a clear stack you can inspect across the languages is awesome stuff.
